onsumer vs. Enterprise & Government)\\n- Advertising sub-categories (display, video, sponsored, etc.)\\n- Geographic revenue breakdown for AI\\n- Gross vs. net (principal vs. agent) dollar split for advertising\\n- **Grok-specific standalone revenue** — never isolated\\n\\n### 3. What the Disclosure PERMITS an Analyst to Conclude About Grok Monetization\\n\\n- **Grok is a material and rapidly growing driver of AI Solutions & Infrastructure revenue.** The MD&A explicitly attributes the $465M YoY increase in AI Solutions & Infrastructure primarily to a $365M increase in \\"X and Grok subscription revenue,\\" and Q1 2026 shows a further $177M increase in \\"Grok and X subscription revenue.\\"\\n- **Grok has a measurable paid subscriber base.** As of March 31, 2026, the filing discloses ~6.3M total active paid subscribers, of which ~1.9M are SuperGrok / SuperGrok Heavy / SuperGrok Lite subscribers (the remainder ~4.4M are X Premium / Premium+).\\n- **Grok is monetized through multiple distinct channels** — consumer subscriptions (sold both standalone via grok.com/mobile apps and integrated into X), API access, and enterprise/government deployments (Grok Business / Grok Enterprise on license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing).\\n- **Grok is sold as a distinct product tier**, not merely a feature of X — the separate subscriber counts and the reference to a \\"stand-alone Grok offering\\" confirm this.\\n- **Future monetization avenues are flagged as opportunities, not realized revenue**: introducing advertising into the standalone Grok offering, and increasing paid penetration across the Grok user base. These are forward-looking and should not be treated as historical outcomes.\\n- **Cost structure is partially attributable to Grok**: higher cost of revenue in FY2025 and Q1 2026 was partially driven by infrastructure, cloud computing, revenue-share, and payment-processing fees tied to increased subscriber revenue.\\n\\n### 4. What the Disclosure Does NOT Permit an Analyst to Conclude About Grok Monetization\\n\\n- **Grok\'s absolute standalone revenue cannot be derived.** Grok subscription revenue is always bundled with X subscription revenue; no dollar split is provided. An analyst cannot compute Grok\'s contribution to the $1,357M AI Solutions & Infrastructure total.\\n- **Grok-specific ARPU cannot be computed.** With ~1.9M Grok subscribers disclosed but Grok revenue not isolated, average revenue per Grok subscriber is not derivable from the filing.\\n- **Grok-specific growth rate cannot be computed.** Only the combined \\"X and Grok\\" YoY change (+$365M) is disclosed; the Grok-only growth rate is unknown.\\n- **API access revenue — including Grok API revenue — is unquantified.** The filing confirms Grok API access is a distinct stream and that the company does not currently sell advertising via the API, but provides no dollar figure, so the size of the developer/API monetization channel is opaque.\\n- **Consumer vs. enterprise Grok revenue split is not disclosed.** Although Grok Business / Grok Enterprise are described qualitatively, their revenue contribution is not separable.\\n- **Grok standalone profitability cannot be assessed.** Cost of revenue increases are attributed to subscriber growth generally, but no Grok-specific cost or margin disclosure exists.\\n- **The relative weight of Grok vs. X within the combined subscription line is unknown.** An analyst cannot infer whether Grok or X is the larger contributor to the +$365M increase.\\n\\n### 5. Bottom Line\\n\\nThe S-1 discloses AI revenue at a **two-line granularity** (Advertising; AI Solutions & Infrastructure) in the financial statements, with a **third qualitative layer** (subscriptions, data licensing, API access) described in policy but quantified only partially via YoY deltas in MD&A. Grok is **always reported bundled with X subscriptions**, and **API access is never quantified**. Consequently, an analyst can confirm that Grok is a fast-growing, multi-channel monetization engine with a disclosed ~1.9M paid subscriber base, but **cannot isolate Grok\'s absolute revenue, ARPU, growth rate, or profitability** from the filing as filed. Any Grok-specific revenue figure would require inference or external data not contained in the S-1.\\n\\n---\\n\\n{\\n  \\"sources\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Consolidated Revenue Table, Revenue Recognition Policy, and MD&A\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}"}',
        parsed_args={
            'final_result': '## AI Segment Revenue Disclosure Analysis — SpaceX S-1 (Filed May 20, 2026)\n\nThe AI segment\'s FY2025 revenue of **$3,201M** is presented in the consolidated revenue table at **two levels of dollar granularity**, with a third qualitative level described in the revenue-recognition policy but not quantified in the tables.\n\n### 1. AI Sub-Components Disclosed WITH Revenue Granularity\n\n| AI Sub-Component | FY2025 | FY2024 | FY2023 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Advertising | $1,844M | $1,728M | $2,323M |\n| AI Solutions & Infrastructure | $1,357M | $892M | $638M |\n| **AI (Total)** | **$3,201M** | **$2,620M** | **$2,961M** |\n\nThe MD&A additionally discloses **year-over-year change amounts** (not absolute balances) for two of the three sub-streams within "AI Solutions & Infrastructure":\n- X and Grok subscription revenue: **+$365M** YoY\n- Data licensing arrangements: **+$88M** YoY\n- (API access change is not separately quantified)\n\n### 2. AI Sub-Components Disclosed WITHOUT Revenue Granularity\n\nThe revenue-recognition policy describes three streams inside "AI Solutions & Infrastructure," but **only the aggregate $1,357M is reported**; none of the three is broken out as an absolute dollar figure:\n\n1. **Premium subscriptions on X and Grok** — recognized ratably (month-to-month up to one year)\n2. **Data licensing arrangements** — recognized ratably (month-to-month up to two years)\n3. **API access to Grok models** — recognized ratably for stand-ready access, or as consumed for usage-based arrangements\n\nThe following are **not disclosed at any dollar level**:\n- Absolute dollar values for subscriptions, data licensing, and API access separately\n- **API access revenue** — never quantified, even as a YoY change\n- **X subscriptions vs. Grok subscriptions split** — always combined as "X and Grok subscription revenue"\n- Consumer vs. enterprise split within AI (unlike Connectivity, which splits Consumer vs. Enterprise & Government)\n- Advertising sub-categories (display, video, sponsored, etc.)\n- Geographic revenue breakdown for AI\n- Gross vs. net (principal vs. agent) dollar split for advertising\n- **Grok-specific standalone revenue** — never isolated\n\n### 3. What the Disclosure PERMITS an Analyst to Conclude About Grok Monetization\n\n- **Grok is a material and rapidly growing driver of AI Solutions & Infrastructure revenue.** The MD&A explicitly attributes the $465M YoY increase in AI Solutions & Infrastructure primarily to a $365M increase in "X and Grok subscription revenue," and Q1 2026 shows a further $177M increase in "Grok and X subscription revenue."\n- **Grok has a measurable paid subscriber base.** As of March 31, 2026, the filing discloses ~6.3M total active paid subscribers, of which ~1.9M are SuperGrok / SuperGrok Heavy / SuperGrok Lite subscribers (the remainder ~4.4M are X Premium / Premium+).\n- **Grok is monetized through multiple distinct channels** — consumer subscriptions (sold both standalone via grok.com/mobile apps and integrated into X), API access, and enterprise/government deployments (Grok Business / Grok Enterprise on license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing).\n- **Grok is sold as a distinct product tier**, not merely a feature of X — the separate subscriber counts and the reference to a "stand-alone Grok offering" confirm this.\n- **Future monetization avenues are flagged as opportunities, not realized revenue**: introducing advertising into the standalone Grok offering, and increasing paid penetration across the Grok user base. These are forward-looking and should not be treated as historical outcomes.\n- **Cost structure is partially attributable to Grok**: higher cost of revenue in FY2025 and Q1 2026 was partially driven by infrastructure, cloud computing, revenue-share, and payment-processing fees tied to increased subscriber revenue.\n\n### 4. What the Disclosure Does NOT Permit an Analyst to Conclude About Grok Monetization\n\n- **Grok\'s absolute standalone revenue cannot be derived.** Grok subscription revenue is always bundled with X subscription revenue; no dollar split is provided. An analyst cannot compute Grok\'s contribution to the $1,357M AI Solutions & Infrastructure total.\n- **Grok-specific ARPU cannot be computed.** With ~1.9M Grok subscribers disclosed but Grok revenue not isolated, average revenue per Grok subscriber is not derivable from the filing.\n- **Grok-specific growth rate cannot be computed.** Only the combined "X and Grok" YoY change (+$365M) is disclosed; the Grok-only growth rate is unknown.\n- **API access revenue — including Grok API revenue — is unquantified.** The filing confirms Grok API access is a distinct stream and that the company does not currently sell advertising via the API, but provides no dollar figure, so the size of the developer/API monetization channel is opaque.\n- **Consumer vs. enterprise Grok revenue split is not disclosed.** Although Grok Business / Grok Enterprise are described qualitatively, their revenue contribution is not separable.\n- **Grok standalone profitability cannot be assessed.** Cost of revenue increases are attributed to subscriber growth generally, but no Grok-specific cost or margin disclosure exists.\n- **The relative weight of Grok vs. X within the combined subscription line is unknown.** An analyst cannot infer whether Grok or X is the larger contributor to the +$365M increase.\n\n### 5. Bottom Line\n\nThe S-1 discloses AI revenue at a **two-line granularity** (Advertising; AI Solutions & Infrastructure) in the financial statements, with a **third qualitative layer** (subscriptions, data licensing, API access) described in policy but quantified only partially via YoY deltas in MD&A. Grok is **always reported bundled with X subscriptions**, and **API access is never quantified**. Consequently, an analyst can confirm that Grok is a fast-growing, multi-channel monetization engine with a disclosed ~1.9M paid subscriber base, but **cannot isolate Grok\'s absolute revenue, ARPU, growth rate, or profitability** from the filing as filed. Any Grok-specific revenue figure would require inference or external data not contained in the S-1.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Consolidated Revenue Table, Revenue Recognition Policy, and MD&A"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
        }
